i prefaced with a lot of the thinking and values that informed my decision. first off i noted that as a teacher i am responsible for the learning of that problematic student but also the rest of the students. i also noted that i have the belief that pretty much nobody ever acts out in such a manner out of malice, and it is almost always due to some other failing or frustration in their life. so basically my first step would be to de-escalate the situation. and prevent it from erupting into a fireball. if that happens i would straight up cancel the exam for that day and reschedule, because half the other students are having test anxiety and that kind of event right by them is just a completely unfair way to assess them. so assuming it could be calmed down, i'd tell the student he didn't have to take the exam that day and direct them to the school counselor/psychologist/headmaster, whoever would be responsible for this kind of thing at their school. then i'd administer the exam to the rest of the students, and afterwards i would seek out the counselor and consult with them on what happened. i'd then follow up with the student privately and go about this a few different ways depending on what the counselor tells me: 1) if there's a personal or familial issue that caused them to act out, i'd encourage them to continue seeing the counselor for some assistance and then work something out about the exam. 2) if it was academic problems that caused the student to lash out, i'd offer tutoring or direct them to resources. i was very emphatic about not disciplining the student in the moment and wanting to do that later when things have calmed down. i also was very emphatic about not involving myself with personal issues or emotions to avoid any dependency or negative association with me and by that the course and subject material
question about problematic student at exam was by far the hardest and most nuanced answer and took a long time

for question about character building in the classroom i said that firstly the chief way to teach character building is to model character yourself. this of course means strict adherence to ethics like citing collaborators and sources and such on everything. being very honest about what is original work and what is not. additionally, i mentioned that when i teach material, i like to also teach a bit about the people who developed the material, both to personalize the material more and for the students to start getting a grasp of the kinds of people who can make these kinds of accomplishments, with the hope that some of them may pursue further study on these figures who can serve as models for them as well

k now for question about widely varying skill i said i would more or less aim my lectures at the median of the class, and try as much as possible to make them self contained (not requiring too much outside of lecture to understand). however this obviously leaves out the extremes of the spectrum, very high performers and very low performers. i proposed for both additional material which was not mandatory and would not be factored into their grade. for high performers add material to keep their interest from waning, in my head i was thinking like advanced open-ended problem sets instead of regular practice. for low performers add material to supplement and fix what i thought were problem areas and weak skills they had that are hindering them. i wanted to write lecture notes for the whole course freely accessible online for students, with those additional supplementary notes also available, so that those students could spend time on their own learning without time constraints.
